  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/9471894" />
    <a title="Virgil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/97004-virgil"><img alt="Virgil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1246237928p2/97004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/9471894?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Virgil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Virgil" href="/user/show/97004-virgil">Virgil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670823598" href="/book/show/55222.The_Second_World_War">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer9471894" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13987588024497287995">A magisterial work. The only thing I would have liked from the book was more discussion of the Battle of the Atlantic, but otherwise I have no complaints. The framing of the book as a series of strategic dilemmas for the major leaders is a simple but effective way of bringing order to a notoriously complex period in history. I can tell why this book made Keegan&apos;s career, and it&apos;s considerably better than his history of the First World War.</span>
  <span id="freeText13987588024497287995" style="display:none">A magisterial work. The only thing I would have liked from the book was more discussion of the Battle of the Atlantic, but otherwise I have no complaints. The framing of the book as a series of strategic dilemmas for the major leaders is a simple but effective way of bringing order to a notoriously complex period in history. I can tell why this book made Keegan's career, and it's considerably better than his history of the First World War.</span>
