    <a title="Nicholas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24221688-nicholas"><img alt="Nicholas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625711768p2/24221688.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/727518840?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nicholas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nicholas" href="/user/show/24221688-nicholas">Nicholas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143035732" href="/book/show/55194.The_Second_World_War">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24221688-nicholas?shelf=wwii">wwii</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer727518840" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1782618982951444705">A fascinating overview of the Second World War! I did find that Keegan focused more on the European than the Pacific theatre, the latter of which sometimes felt like it was getting short changed in attention and detail. As well, he tends to focus primarily on military campaigns - which makes sense given the topic of the book, but I still would have appreciated some more discussion of aspects of the war like the holocaust, research and development, civilian life during the war, intelligence effor</span>
  <span id="freeText1782618982951444705" style="display:none">A fascinating overview of the Second World War! I did find that Keegan focused more on the European than the Pacific theatre, the latter of which sometimes felt like it was getting short changed in attention and detail. As well, he tends to focus primarily on military campaigns - which makes sense given the topic of the book, but I still would have appreciated some more discussion of aspects of the war like the holocaust, research and development, civilian life during the war, intelligence efforts, and so forth. Still, with only 600 or so pages to cover the entirety of the war, this book does a good job of presenting some of its major points.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1782618982951444705" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


